The paper discusses a course on domain-specific languages (DSLs) for mathematics, which involves programming and functional programming concepts. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on education and student results, indicating that it could also belong to the Education (cs.ED) sub-category. The use of DSLs also suggests that the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category could be relevant. The evaluation of student results could also fall under the Measurement and Analysis of Software (cs.MS) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the challenges of continuing on to more advanced courses, which could relate to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category.
